Endgame is acclaimed biographer Frank BradyÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s decades-in-the-making tracing of the meteoric ascentÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½and confounding descentÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½of enigmatic genius Bobby Fischer. Only Brady, who met Fischer when the prodigy was only 10 and shared with him some of his most dramatic triumphs, could have written this book, which has much to say about the nature of American celebrity and the distorting effects of fame. Drawing from Fischer family archives, recently released FBI files, and BobbyÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s own emails, this account is unique in that it limns FischerÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s entire lifeÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½an odyssey that took the Brooklyn-raised chess champion from an impoverished childhood to the covers of Time, Life and Newsweek to recognition as ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œthe most famous man in the worldÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ to notorious recluse.At first all one noticed was how gifted Fischer was. Possessing a 181 I.Q. and remarkable powers of concentration, Bobby memorized hundreds of chess books in several languages, and he was only 13 when he became the youngest chess master in U.S. history. But his strange behavior started early. In 1972, at the historic Cold War showdown in Reykjavik, Iceland, where he faced Soviet champion Boris Spassky, Fischer made headlines with hundreds of petty demands that nearly ended the competition.

It was merely a prelude to what was to come.

Arriving back in the United States to a heroÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s welcome, Bobby was mobbed wherever he wentÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½a figure as exotic and improbable as any American pop culture had yet produced. No player of a mere ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œboard gameÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ had ever ascended to such heights. Commercial sponsorship offers poured in, ultimately topping $10 millionÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½but Bobby demurred. Instead, he began tithing his limited money to an apocalyptic religion and devouring anti-Semitic literature.
After years of poverty and a stint living on Los AngelesÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ Skid Row, Bobby remerged in 1992 to play Spassky in a multi-million dollar rematchÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½but the experience only deepened a paranoia that had formed years earlier when he came to believe that the Soviets wanted him dead for taking away ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œtheirÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ title. When the dust settled, Bobby was a wanted manÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½transformed into an international fugitive because of his decision to play in Montenegro despite U.S. sanctions. Fearing for his life, traveling with bodyguards, and wearing a long leather coat to ward off knife attacks, Bobby lived the life of a celebrity fugitive ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ one drawn increasingly to the bizarre. Mafiosi, Nazis, odd attempts to breed an heir who could perpetuate his chess-genius DNAÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½all are woven into his late-life tapestry.
And yet, as Brady shows, the most notable irony of Bobby FischerÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s strange descent ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ which had reached full plummet by 2005 when he turned down yet another multi-million dollar paydayÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½is that despite his incomprehensible behavior, there were many who remained fiercely loyal to him. Why that was so is at least partly the subject of this bookÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬ï¿½one that at last answers the question: ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œWho was Bobby Fischer?ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½
